"id": "a4-liquidation-waterfall-priority",
"problem_text": "Firm X is being liquidated. Its assets are sold for $120 million in cash. The capital structure consists of (1) a secured bank loan with face value $60 million, (2) unsecured bonds with face value $50 million, (3) mezzanine debt with face value $20 million, and (4) common equity. Assume absolute priority: the bank loan is paid first, then the unsecured bonds, then mezzanine, then equity. You are asked to (1) compute the recovery to each class, (2) compute the recovery rates as a percentage of face value, and (3) explain how priority affects risk for each layer.",
"archetype": "A4-PriorityAndRiskShifting",
"solution_steps": [
{
"part": "Step 1 - Reconnaissance",
"prompt": "Why is this a priority / waterfall problem?",
"reasoning": "We have a fixed asset value at liquidation and multiple layers of claims with specified seniority. The question asks how the cash is split across tranches. That is the classic A4 priority and waterfall setup.",
"calculation": "Signals:\n- Asset value in liquidation explicitly given.\n- Multiple tranches: secured, unsecured, mezz, equity.\n- Absolute priority rule spelled out.\n- Need to compute recoveries and recovery rates.\n=> Archetype A4: Distress, Priority, and Hybrid Claims.",
"sanity_check": "Any time you see 'Firm in bankruptcy' plus an ordered list of claims and cash to distribute, think A4 waterfall."
},
{
"part": "Step 2 - Allocate Cash by Priority",
"prompt": "Apply the absolute priority rule.",
"reasoning": "We start from the top of the capital structure and pay each tranche up to its face value, as long as there is cash left. Any remaining cash flows to the next tranche down, and so on.",
"calculation": "Total cash available: 120.\n\n1) Secured bank loan (face 60):\n   Pay min(60, 120) = 60.\n   Remaining cash: 120 − 60 = 60.\n\n2) Unsecured bonds (face 50):\n   Pay min(50, 60) = 50.\n   Remaining cash: 60 − 50 = 10.\n\n3) Mezzanine debt (face 20):\n   Pay min(20, 10) = 10.\n   Remaining cash: 10 − 10 = 0.\n\n4) Equity:\n   Equity gets the residual, which is 0.",
"sanity_check": "The sum of recoveries should equal the total asset value: 60 + 50 + 10 + 0 = 120."
},
{
"part": "Step 3 - Compute Recovery Rates",
"prompt": "Express recoveries as percentages of face value.",
"reasoning": "Recovery rates are often used to estimate expected returns and credit loss severity. They tell us which layer bears most of the loss.",
"calculation": "Recovery rates:\n- Secured bank loan: 60 / 60 = 100%.\n- Unsecured bonds: 50 / 50 = 100%.\n- Mezzanine debt: 10 / 20 = 50%.\n- Equity: 0 / (residual claim) = 0%.\n\nLoss rates:\n- Mezzanine loses 50% of principal.\n- Equity loses 100% of its residual claim.",
"sanity_check": "Senior secured debt typically has the highest recovery rate; junior debt and equity bear the brunt of losses. That’s exactly what we see here."
},
{
"part": "Step 4 - Interpret Priority and Risk",
"prompt": "Explain what this says about risk and expected returns.",
"reasoning": "Higher priority means lower loss severity in distress and thus lower credit risk. Investors in junior tranches require higher promised yields to compensate for higher expected losses.",
"calculation": "Implications:\n- Secured bank lenders are virtually risk-free in this scenario (100% recovery). They should earn a low spread over the risk-free rate.\n- Unsecured bondholders also recover fully here but will be more exposed in worse states of the world.\n- Mezzanine investors suffer a 50% loss; they require a high promised return to compensate for such outcomes.\n- Equity is wiped out; it bears the residual risk and hence demands the highest ex-ante expected return.",
"sanity_check": "If an exam gives you a waterfall where junior tranches recover more than senior ones, they are either testing your ability to spot a mistake or there is some specific contractual twist (e.g., structural subordination vs. security). In plain priority problems, senior claims should never recover less than junior ones."
},
{
"part": "Step 5 - Connection to Capital Structure Design",
"prompt": "Relate waterfall outcomes to optimal capital structure.",
"reasoning": "Understanding how different tranches fare in distress helps explain why firms choose layered capital structures. It also ties back to agency problems like risk-shifting and underinvestment.",
"calculation": "Design tradeoffs:\n- Senior secured debt lowers cost of capital but may encourage equity to take more risk (risk-shifting), because downside is absorbed by creditors.\n- Mezzanine and equity absorb losses and thus discipline risk-taking but are expensive.\n\nIn this example:\n- If X added more mezzanine rather than senior debt, the marginal cost of distress for the mezz tranche could be very high.\n- Equity might prefer risky strategies that push value into good states at the expense of mezz or unsecured creditors.",
"sanity_check": "On conceptual parts, you can always tie waterfall outcomes back to why senior creditors care about covenants and why equity may favor risk-shifting when there is a lot of safe senior debt ahead of them."
}
],
