{
"part": "Step 4 - Compare Firm vs Equity Preferences",
"prompt": "Which project is better for the firm? Which do equity holders prefer?",
"reasoning": "We must distinguish firm-wide value (total claims) from equity’s value. Risk-shifting occurs when equity prefers a project that reduces total firm value but increases equity value.",
"calculation": "Firm values:\n- V_safe ≈ 127.27.\n- V_risky ≈ 109.09.\n=> The safe project is better for the firm (higher total value).\n\nEquity values:\n- P_E_safe ≈ 18.18.\n- P_E_risky ≈ 36.36.\n=> Equity prefers the risky project (higher equity value).\n\nDebt values:\n- P_D_safe ≈ 109.09.\n- P_D_risky ≈ 72.73.\n=> Creditors heavily prefer the safe project.",
"sanity_check": "This is the classic pattern: risky project lowers firm value but doubles equity value, with creditors absorbing the downside."
