{
"part": "Step 5 - Interpretation: Risk-Shifting",
"prompt": "Explain the mechanism of risk-shifting.",
"reasoning": "With limited liability and fixed face value debt, equity captures upside beyond the debt face but does not bear the full downside (creditors share it). This asymmetry can make equity favor riskier projects that reduce total firm value.",
"calculation": "Mechanism:\n- Under the safe project, equity has a small upside (40 in the good state) and no downside in the bad state; creditors are fully protected.\n- Under the risky project, equity doubles its upside (80 in the good state) but is still wiped out in the bad state, which was largely the case under the safe project too.\n- The extra downside of 80 vs 120 in the bad state falls entirely on creditors (40 recovery vs 120), not on equity.\n\nResult:\n- Equity’s expected payoff increases (and so does P_E), even though the expected asset payoff and overall firm value fall.",
"sanity_check": "On exams, when you see equity choosing a project with lower firm value but higher equity value, you should immediately label this risk-shifting or asset substitution."
}
],
