"reasoning": "The firm-level NPV ignores who gets the project’s cash flows; it simply compares the present value of the incremental asset payoffs to the project cost.",
"calculation": "Without project, asset payoffs at t=1:\n- Good: 160.\n- Bad: 80.\nExpected payoff = 0.5 * 160 + 0.5 * 80 = 120.\nPresent value without project:\n  V_assets,0 = 120 / 1.10 = 109.09.\n\nWith project, asset payoffs become:\n- Good: 160 + 40 = 200.\n- Bad: 80 + 40 = 120.\nExpected payoff = 0.5 * 200 + 0.5 * 120 = 160.\nPresent value with project (before deducting cost):\n  V_assets,0^project = 160 / 1.10 = 145.45.\n\nProject NPV at asset level:\n  NPV_project = 145.45 − 109.09 − 20 ≈ 16.36.\nSo the project is positive NPV for the firm.",
"sanity_check": "The expected payoff increases by 40 in each state, so the expected increase in payoff is 40. Discounting at 10% gives about 36.36 of PV gain. Subtracting the 20 cost yields roughly 16.36, so the project is clearly positive NPV."
},
{
"part": "Step 3 - Value of Debt and Equity Without the Project",
"prompt": "Compute current values of debt and equity given the existing capital structure.",
"reasoning": "We first need the status quo values before adding the project. Debt gets paid first up to its face value; equity gets the residual. Values are discounted at the 10% asset required return for these risky claims.",
"calculation": "Without project, t=1 payoffs:\n- Good state (V = 160): Debt gets 120, equity gets 160 − 120 = 40.\n- Bad state (V = 80): Debt gets 80 (firm liquidated), equity gets 0.\n\nDebt value:\n  P_D0 = [0.5 * 120 + 0.5 * 80] / 1.10\n        = (60 + 40) / 1.10\n        = 100 / 1.10\n        ≈ 90.91.\nEquity value:\n  P_E0 = [0.5 * 40 + 0.5 * 0] / 1.10\n        = 20 / 1.10\n        ≈ 18.18.\nTotal firm value:\n  90.91 + 18.18 = 109.09 (matches asset PV above).",
"sanity_check": "Firm value from claims (debt + equity) should match the unlevered asset PV (109.09). If not, you misallocated payoffs or mis-discounted something."
},
{
"part": "Step 4 - Value of Debt and Equity With the Project (Before Financing Cost)",
"prompt": "Recompute values if the project were implemented, ignoring who pays for it.",
"reasoning": "We treat the project as if the firm magically adds the project’s payoff stream without worrying yet about the financing cost. This isolates who benefits from the extra cash flows under the existing priority structure.",
"calculation": "With project, t=1 payoffs:\n- Good: V = 200.\n- Bad: V = 120.\nDebt (face 120) payoffs:\n- Good: 120.\n- Bad: 120.\n=> Debt is now risk-free.\n\nDebt value:\n  P_D1 = [0.5 * 120 + 0.5 * 120] / 1.10\n        = 120 / 1.10\n        ≈ 109.09.\n\nEquity payoffs:\n- Good: 200 − 120 = 80.\n- Bad: 120 − 120 = 0.\nEquity value:\n  P_E1 = [0.5 * 80 + 0.5 * 0] / 1.10\n        = 40 / 1.10\n        ≈ 36.36.\n\nTotal firm value before subtracting cost:\n  109.09 + 36.36 = 145.45 (matches asset PV with project).",
"sanity_check": "Debt becomes risk-free because in both states assets ≥ 120. Its value rising from ~90.91 to ~109.09 indicates a big gain for debtholders. Equity’s value also rises from ~18.18 to ~36.36 if we ignore the cost of the project for a moment."
},
{
"part": "Step 5 - Equity-Financed Project and Old Equity’s Wealth",
"prompt": "Account for the financing cost via new equity issuance.",
"reasoning": "The project costs 20 today. If new equity is issued at a fair price, new investors pay 20 and receive claims worth 20. Old equity’s wealth is the residual: new equity value minus what new investors paid.",
"calculation": "With project, total equity value P_E1 ≈ 36.36. New investors contribute 20, so they must receive shares worth 20, leaving:\n  Wealth of old equity after = P_E1 − 20 ≈ 36.36 − 20 = 16.36.\n\nWealth of old equity before project:\n  P_E0 ≈ 18.18.\n\nChange in old equity wealth:\n  ΔW_old ≈ 16.36 − 18.18 ≈ −1.82.\nSo old equity holders lose about 1.82 even though the project has positive NPV for the firm.",
"sanity_check": "This is the key overhang result: firm-level NPV ≈ +16.36, but old equity loses wealth ≈ −1.82 if they fund it. This type of sign flip is what you are looking for in a debt overhang question."
},
{
