"id": "a4-risk-shifting-senior-vs-junior",
"problem_text": "Firm Y has debt with face value $120 due in 1 year. It must choose between two mutually exclusive projects: Safe and Risky. Both require the same investment today and are financed entirely with existing capital (no new securities). Project Safe yields asset values of $160 (good) or $120 (bad) with equal probability. Project Risky yields $200 (good) or $40 (bad) with equal probability. The required return on assets is 10%. You are asked to (1) compute firm value and equity value under each project, (2) determine which project is better for the firm as a whole, and (3) explain why equity holders may prefer a project that reduces firm value (risk-shifting).",
"archetype": "A4-PriorityAndRiskShifting",
"solution_steps": [
{
"part": "Step 1 - Reconnaissance",
"prompt": "Why is this a risk-shifting problem?",
"reasoning": "The firm already has debt in place and must choose between a safer project and a riskier one with different payoff distributions but similar funding needs. The question asks who benefits under each project. That is the standard A4 risk-shifting / asset-substitution pattern.",
"calculation": "Signals:\n- Existing fixed debt with priority.\n- Two alternative asset payoff distributions with same initial cost.\n- Equity vs total firm value comparison.\n=> Archetype A4: Distress, Priority, and Risk-Shifting.",
"sanity_check": "Whenever you see 'choose a riskier project' after debt is already issued, think about whether equity gains at creditors’ expense."
},
{
"part": "Step 2 - Firm and Equity Values under Project Safe",
"prompt": "Compute firm value and equity value for the safer project.",
"reasoning": "Firm value is the PV of expected asset payoffs discounted at the asset required return. Equity value is the PV of equity’s residual payoffs after debt is paid.",
"calculation": "Project Safe asset payoffs at t=1:\n- Good: 160.\n- Bad: 120.\nExpected payoff = 0.5 * 160 + 0.5 * 120 = 140.\nFirm value:\n  V_safe = 140 / 1.10 ≈ 127.27.\n\nDebt payoffs (face 120):\n- Good: 120.\n- Bad: 120.\n=> Debt is risk-free here.\nDebt value:\n  P_D_safe = 120 / 1.10 ≈ 109.09.\n\nEquity payoffs:\n- Good: 160 − 120 = 40.\n- Bad: 120 − 120 = 0.\nEquity value:\n  P_E_safe = [0.5 * 40 + 0.5 * 0] / 1.10 = 20 / 1.10 ≈ 18.18.",
"sanity_check": "Firm value should equal debt + equity: 127.27 ≈ 109.09 + 18.18."
},
{
"part": "Step 3 - Firm and Equity Values under Project Risky",
"prompt": "Compute firm value and equity value for the riskier project.",
"reasoning": "Same approach: compute firm value from expected payoffs, and equity value as the residual after paying debt.",
"calculation": "Project Risky asset payoffs at t=1:\n- Good: 200.\n- Bad: 40.\nExpected payoff = 0.5 * 200 + 0.5 * 40 = 120.\nFirm value:\n  V_risky = 120 / 1.10 ≈ 109.09.\n\nDebt payoffs:\n- Good: 120.\n- Bad: min(40, 120) = 40.\nDebt value:\n  P_D_risky = [0.5 * 120 + 0.5 * 40] / 1.10\n            = (60 + 20) / 1.10\n            = 80 / 1.10 ≈ 72.73.\n\nEquity payoffs:\n- Good: 200 − 120 = 80.\n- Bad: max(40 − 120, 0) = 0.\nEquity value:\n  P_E_risky = [0.5 * 80 + 0.5 * 0] / 1.10\n             = 40 / 1.10 ≈ 36.36.",
"sanity_check": "Again, firm value ≈ debt + equity: 109.09 ≈ 72.73 + 36.36."
},
{
"part": "Step 4 - Compare Firm vs Equity Preferences",
"prompt": "Which project is better for the firm? Which do equity holders prefer?",
"reasoning": "We must distinguish firm-wide value (total claims) from equity’s value. Risk-shifting occurs when equity prefers a project that reduces total firm value but increases equity value.",
"calculation": "Firm values:\n- V_safe ≈ 127.27.\n- V_risky ≈ 109.09.\n=> The safe project is better for the firm (higher total value).\n\nEquity values:\n- P_E_safe ≈ 18.18.\n- P_E_risky ≈ 36.36.\n=> Equity prefers the risky project (higher equity value).\n\nDebt values:\n- P_D_safe ≈ 109.09.\n- P_D_risky ≈ 72.73.\n=> Creditors heavily prefer the safe project.",
"sanity_check": "This is the classic pattern: risky project lowers firm value but doubles equity value, with creditors absorbing the downside."
},
{
"part": "Step 5 - Interpretation: Risk-Shifting",
"prompt": "Explain the mechanism of risk-shifting.",
"reasoning": "With limited liability and fixed face value debt, equity captures upside beyond the debt face but does not bear the full downside (creditors share it). This asymmetry can make equity favor riskier projects that reduce total firm value.",
"calculation": "Mechanism:\n- Under the safe project, equity has a small upside (40 in the good state) and no downside in the bad state; creditors are fully protected.\n- Under the risky project, equity doubles its upside (80 in the good state) but is still wiped out in the bad state, which was largely the case under the safe project too.\n- The extra downside of 80 vs 120 in the bad state falls entirely on creditors (40 recovery vs 120), not on equity.\n\nResult:\n- Equity’s expected payoff increases (and so does P_E), even though the expected asset payoff and overall firm value fall.",
"sanity_check": "On exams, when you see equity choosing a project with lower firm value but higher equity value, you should immediately label this risk-shifting or asset substitution."
}
],
"key_insights": [
"Risk-shifting arises because equity’s payoff is convex: limited downside but unlimited upside.",
"Creditors bear much of the downside when projects become riskier, so equity may rationally favor those projects.",
"This agency problem explains why debt contracts often include covenants restricting risk-taking."
],
"common_mistakes": [
"Conflating 'best for equity' with 'best for the firm' when there is substantial debt.",
"Ignoring priority, which hides that creditors absorb much of the downside in the risky project.",
"Failing to compute both firm value and equity value before labeling a situation as risk-shifting."
